[2] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Fri 18 Feb 2009
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/pais/mat/2009/02/18/mortes-por-dengue-hemorragica-deixam-bahia-em-alerta-754469326.asp>


The 1st case of DHF in Salvador was confirmed, and at least 7 people
have been admitted to hospital as having contracted this most serious
form of the [dengue] disease. According to the Couto Maia hospital,
there are 3 children and 4 adults. In Itabuna, a 4-year-old child
died, a victim of DHF.

Since the beginning of the year [2009], 6 people suspected of having
dengue died. Up to the present, 2 cases were confirmed.

The municipality has declared an emergency due to the epidemic of the
disease. Technical personnel of the Ministry of Health and of the
state government are in the city. They are analyzing the situation
and are planning strategies to combat the focal areas of mosquito
[breeding] and to attend to patients who are victims of dengue.

The city's hospitals are full of patients with symptoms of dengue.
According to doctors, the dengue cases that occurred in Jequie have
the more aggressive type of the disease.

The city asked the Public Ministry to authorize access for health
workers to the 1200 buildings that are closed in the city. If the
authorization is granted, the officers may break into the properties
with the support of the Military Police. The judge of the 11th civil
and commercial court said that he is not authorized to give such
approval. This process is in the Public Finance court.

Just in January this year [2009], 4242 [dengue] cases were reported
in the state of Bahia. This number reflects an increase of 116
percent over the same period of last year [2008].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[3] Brazil (Para)
Date: Thu 18 Feb 2009
Source: Diario do Para [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.diariodopara.com.br/noticiafull.php?idnot=30536>


The numbers of suspected dengue cases continue to increase. In just
15 days of February [2009], 12 children were admitted to the Joao de
Barros Barreto University Hospital, presenting with symptoms of the
disease. According to Vivian Cartagenes, Coordinator of the
epidemiological surveillance nucleus of Barros Barreto, despite the
number [of dengue cases] considered as being high, they continue to
be less than in January of this year [2009], when 20 suspected cases
were registered. Of these [current cases], 6 were confirmed, with 4
classified as dengue with complications, and 2 were DHF. According to
the Coordinator, 5 children continue to be attended to in the
hospital. "The other children were released but continue to await
results of laboratory tests."

The Coordinator stated that the number of suspected cases in Belem
must be higher than announced. "Many public and private hospitals do
not report cases. Where are the numbers from the other hospitals? All
the health professionals must report dengue cases. When they do not
do this, it is difficult to maintain control [of the disease].
Everyone needs to be aware that dengue kills," stated Vivian.
According to her, this year, there have been no recorded deaths due
to the disease. The Coordinator explained that in most cases, dengue
has had a benign course.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Wed 17 Feb 2009
Source: A Noticia [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.anoticiadigital.com.br/home/news.asp?cod=50196>


Mato Grosso had 9 cases of hemorrhagic dengue confirmed since the
beginning of rainy season, which began in November 2008. The
municipalities of Cuiaba, Varzea Grande and Rosario Oeste had 2 cases
each. Already, Tangara of Serra was highest in notifications, with 3
occurrences [cases] and one death, which is undergoing investigation
for confirmation of the cause [of death]. The technical person of the
dengue program in the State Secretariat for Health, Rita Cristina
Martins, explained that hemorrhage is a complication of the disease;
in its classic form, it can kill in up to 24 hours.

In the municipality of Sierra de Tanger (239 km [149 miles]
north-central from the Capital), all affected [dengue patients] are
children. The technical person of Epidemiological Surveillance of the
municipality, Juliana Marques da Silva, announced that the patients
were 3, 4, 7 and one year of age. She talks about the events that
took the organization by surprise, and, in the neighborhoods where
people live, chemicals were used to kill the vector [mosquito].

Martins stated that there is still a high number of under reported
[cases]. The people tend to self-medicate and not seek medical care.
This fact affects the formation of an efficient fight against the
disease. She explained that application of chemicals or barriers are
done only when there is an outbreak in the area. Otherwise, it is
best to visit health workers. The number of cases may increase in
coming days due to rain.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

