[5] Bolivia (eastern lowlands)
Date: Sun 22 Feb 2009
Source: MSN Latino [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://salud.latino.msn.com/noticias/articlepage.aspx?cp-documentid=100233192>


The government of President Evo Morales decided to redouble its
efforts to combat dengue in the face of the report of more than 22
000 suspected cases.

"We see that the number of dengue cases will increase, and we wish to
guarantee that there are no deaths from DHF; that is why we are
redoubling our efforts to combat dengue," said the Minister of
Health, Ramiro Tapia, in statements made on the national radio Patria
Nueva.

"Now we are awaiting the arrival of a significant donation from the
government of Venezuela which will be finalized tomorrow [23 Feb
2009], which includes more than 20 tons of materials for fumigation
and the arrival of 10 experts. This is one of the more important
donations," said the Minister.

The Bolivian government declared a health emergency and laid out a
large fumigation plan with the help of soldiers, universities and
personnel from the Church in order to control propagation of the
disease.

According to the latest epidemiological report of the Ministry of
Health, 15 people have died of DHF, and 2118 confirmed cases of
classical dengue have been recorded. There are more than 22 000
suspected [dengue] cases, 70 percent of which have been recorded in
the department [state or province equivalent] of Santa Cruz.

Tapia also announced the arrival of a group of Mexican experts in the
next few days.

"We are grateful for international collaboration with Mexico,
Venezuela as well as Cuba. One of the best Cuban experts is now
incorporated in the Bolivian team for fighting dengue," explained the
Minister.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Bolivia's eastern lowland departments of Santa Cruz, Beni,
Cochabamba and Pando continue to suffer a significant dengue
outbreak. Dengue virus types 1 and 3 were reported circulating in
Bolivia by the Pan American Health Organization release of 17 Feb
2009 (sent in by ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp)
(<http://new.paho.org/hq/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=706&Itemid=1>).
Help with the dengue campaign is also being provided by Paraguay
(reported in MSN Latino in Spanish, posted in ProMED-PORT,
<http://salud.latino.msn.com/noticias/articlepage.aspx?cp-documentid=100233192>
with 4000 liters of insecticide and 1000 liters of larvacide. The 20
Feb 2009 edition of FM Bolivia (in Spanish)
<http://www.fmbolivia.com.bo/noticia8748-japon-y-espana-ayudaran-para-enfrentar-epidemia-del-dengue.html>
reported that Japan and Spain were also providing assistance. One
hopes that with the help the Bolivian Ministry of Health is
receiving, the outbreak can be slowed or halted soon.

A map of Bolivia showing the departments can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_admin_2006.jpg>.

