[7] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Sat 21 Feb 2009
Source: The Australian [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25085147-5006786,00.html>


The dengue fever epidemic in far north Queensland has spread to the
small Aboriginal community of Yarrabah. Queensland Health yesterday
[20 Feb 2009] reported 2 cases of the mosquito-borne disease at
Yarrabah, south of Cairns.

Cairns has 416 dengue cases; Townsville has 66, and Port Douglas has 2.

In northern Queensland, 3 types of dengue virus have been detected so
far, increasing the chances residents could develop a potentially
fatal re-infection.

Deaths from dengue fever occur when someone who has recovered from
one infection is re-infected by a different type of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
Health Map <promed@promedmail.org>

[The 12 Feb 2009 edition of The Cairns Post
<http://www.cairns.com.au/article/2009/02/12/28311_local-news.html>
reported that the 3 dengue viruses circulating in Queensland are
DEN-2 and DEN-3 in Cairns and DEN-1 and DEN-2 in Townsville.

A map of Australia showing the location of Queensland state and the
cities mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/australia/australia_pol99.jpg>.
