[8] Malaysia
Date: Mon 16 Feb 2009
Source: New Straits Times [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Monday/NewsBreak/20090216161432/Article/index_html>


For the 5th week [of 2009] ending 7 Feb 2009, 3 more people have died
from dengue fever, bringing the total deaths so far to 18 compared to
only 7 for the corresponding period last year [2008].

Health Minister Datuk Liow Tiong Lai said 1232 cases were reported
compared to 1013 cases the previous week, an increase of 219 cases of
which 50 percent were from Selangor.

"Eight states had recorded increases led by Kelantan (162 percent),
Johor (40 percent), Selangor (33 percent), Perak (18 percent), Sabah
(13 percent), Melaka (10 percent), Pahang (8 percent) and Sarawak (2
percent)," he said in a statement in Kuala Lumpur today [16 Feb 2009].

Some 13 new "hot dengue areas" had been identified bringing the total
to 39. Selangor had the largest number with 33, followed by Wilayah
Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur-Putrajaya with 4, while Johor and Sarawak
had one each.

Liow said checks by local authorities found that 1672 premises were
breeding grounds for _Aedes_ mosquitoes and that 74 percent comprised
houses and shophouses.

He urged State Health Departments to step up prevention and control
efforts aimed at reducing the number of "hot" dengue areas.

"This is in line with the ministry's efforts to reduce the number of
dengue cases by 10 percent annually," he added.

In Kuching, Environment and Public Health Minister Datuk Seri Wong
Soon Koh said no major dengue outbreak had been reported in Sarawak
despite new cases recorded recently. "The dengue situation is still
under control. There is denial of such a thing, and he said the
Health Department report from 10-15 Feb [2009] stated there were 8
cases and that none were from Carpenter Street.

He said most of the patients were given out-patient treatment and
some had been discharged.

--
